  <div id="grooming" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Grooming: Easy Coat, One Daily Ritual" imageAlt="Pug puppy having its facial wrinkles gently cleaned" imageSrc={imgScene3} imagePosition="left">
      <p>Coat care is the easy part: a weekly brush (which also helps manage the honestly impressive shedding) and an occasional bath. No mats, no salon schedule, no topknots.</p>
      <p>The part that actually matters is the wrinkles. Those famous facial folds trap moisture, and in our humidity a neglected fold turns red and sore within days. The ritual: a gentle wipe through every fold daily, then dry; thirty seconds total, and the wet wipes for it are in your starter kit. Add a weekly nail trim and the day-one tooth-brushing habit and that's the entire Pug grooming manual.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>

  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" />
  <div id="health" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Pug Health: What We Check Before You Take One Home" imageAlt="Pug puppy at a veterinary health check before going home" imageSrc={imgScene4} variant="mid">
      <p>Every Pug goes home vet-checked, vaccinated, dewormed, and microchipped. The Pug health points worth knowing, stated plainly because this breed deserves informed owners: brachycephalic airway syndrome, the flat-face breathing trade-off, which makes heat and overexertion the two things to manage for life; obesity, the most common and most preventable Pug problem, controlled entirely by your portion discipline; the prominent eyes, which scratch easily and deserve a vet look at the first sign of squinting; and skin fold dermatitis, prevented by the daily wrinkle ritual above.</p>
      <p>Feeding is simple: your puppy comes with the food it is already eating, and any change should be gradual over a week. For portioning guidance, which matters more for the Pug than any breed we carry, see the <a href="/learn/puppy-health/" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">puppy health checks explained</a> guide.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>
  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" flip />

  <div class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Living Flat-Faced in Singapore: The Heat Rules" imagePosition="none" variant="card">
      <p>We put this on every flat-faced breed page we write, because it is the difference between a thriving Pug and an emergency vet visit. Dogs cool themselves by panting; a brachycephalic dog pants inefficiently, and Singapore sits at 30-plus degrees with tropical humidity most of the year.</p>
      <p>The rules: walks before 9am or after 6pm, never midday; shade and water on every outing; a cool, ventilated room at home, with fan or aircon through the afternoon; and know the emergency signs: relentless heavy panting, a very dark red tongue, wobbliness. Cool water on the body, aircon, and the vet, in that order.</p>
      <div slot="side" class="clay h-full bg-[var(--color-peach-100)] p-6 sm:p-8">
        <p class="text-xs font-bold uppercase text-[var(--color-cream-500)]" style="letter-spacing: 0.08em;">The heat rules</p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-3">
          {[
            'Walks before 9am or after 6pm only',
            'Cool, ventilated room through the afternoon',
            'Keep it lean; extra weight makes breathing harder',
          ].map((fact) => (
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-[var(--color-cream-700)]">
              <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" class="mt-0.5 shrink-0 text-[var(--color-coral-500)]" aria-hidden="true">
                <path d="M20 6 9 17l-5-5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" />
              </svg>
              {fact}
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      </div>
    </CaptionedBlock>

    <PawTrail bg="bg-[var(--color-surface)]" colorClass="text-[var(--color-coral-300)]" />
  </div>

  <CaptionedBlock heading="Your Pug's First Week at Home" imageAlt="Pug puppy settling into a set-up playpen during its first week home" imageSrc={imgScene5} imagePosition="left">
    <p>Day 0: we deliver, free, at a time that suits you, usually morning or evening. The playpen, bed, water, and toys are set up before your Pug explores the room, and we walk you through all 30+ starter-kit items in person. Learn more about <a href="/delivery/" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">how our free home delivery and setup works</a>.</p>
    <p>Days 1 to 3: keep it calm, cool and predictable. A fixed feeding routine with measured portions from the very first meal, the toilet pads where we placed them, and the wrinkle-wipe ritual starting immediately so it becomes normal. Some night snoring is not adjustment; that's permanent, and most owners come to love it.</p>
    <p>Days 4 to 7: the routine sticks. Book your free first lesson with an AVS-certified trainer this week; see <a href="/free-training/" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">what the free AVS-certified training lesson covers</a>. For anything in between, you WhatsApp us.</p>
  </CaptionedBlock>

